  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Statement.}\n\nPersistence-diagram entropy is obtained by converting topological lifetimes into a normalized probability distribution and measuring the information carried by that distribution.\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\n\nLet\n\\[\nD=\\{(b_i,d_i)\\}_{i=1}^{N}\n\\]\nbe a persistence diagram with lifetimes\n\\[\n\\ell_i=d_i-b_i,\\qquad \\ell_i\\ge 0.\n\\]\nThe total persistence mass is\n\\[\nL_D=\\sum_{i=1}^{N}\\ell_i.\n\\]\nWhen \\(L_D>0\\), define normalized persistence weights by\n\\[\np_i=\\frac{\\ell_i}{L_D},\\qquad \\sum_{i=1}^{N}p_i=1.\n\\]\nThe persistence entropy is therefore\n\\begin{equation}\nS_D=-\\sum_{i=1}^{N}p_i\\log p_i.\n\\end{equation}\nTo include Wasserstein sensitivity, let \\(D'\\) be a comparison diagram and let\n\\[\nW_p(D,D')=\\left(\\inf_{\\gamma:D\\to D'}\\sum_{x\\in D}\\|x-\\gamma(x)\\|^{p}\\right)^{1/p}\n\\]\nbe the \\(p\\)-Wasserstein distance between matched diagrams. A normalized stability score may be written as\n\\[\n\\mathcal{S}_{W}(D,D')=\\frac{S_D}{1+W_p(D,D')}.\n\\]\n\n\\paragraph{Wolfram Form.}\n\\begin{verbatim}\nlifetimes = d - b;\nweights = lifetimes/Total[lifetimes];\nSD = -Total[weights*Log[weights]];\nSW = SD/(1 + Wp[D, Dp, p]);\n\\end{verbatim}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\n\nID 0226 measures how much topological information is carried by persistent features, then tempers that entropy by the Wasserstein displacement needed to move one diagram into another.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
